@planersibling: If you cast an Aura as a spell, it has to target something so the game knows what it's supposed to be attached to. That's the only part where shroud has an effect on Auras. If another effect puts an Aura onto the battlefield, you choose an object for it to enchant, and things with shroud are fair game unless the effect says it targets the object to attach it to (which this doesn't).

The things that restrict what an Aura can legally enchant are the specifics of "enchant whatever" and protection. As the ruling cites, you can't attach a black Aura to a creature with protection from black (or from enchantments). You also can't attach an "enchant land" or "enchant player" Aura to a creature, you can't attach "enchant tapped creature" to an untapped creature, and so on.

I'm pretty sure [autocard]Animate Dead[/autocard] doesn't work with this, since Animate Dead enchants a creature card in a graveyard initially. There's a rule (I'm paraphrasing here) that says whenever an effect refers to a creature it means one on the battlefield unless it explicitly says otherwise, so effectively there would never be anything Animate Dead could legally enchant out of the choices that could be provided by this card's ability.

